482
00:41:02,655 --> 00:41:03,975
Valentine's Day is soon

483
00:41:04,030 --> 00:41:08,899
and I want to give Damian a present
so he can love me.

484
00:41:09,239 --> 00:41:12,239
Can you explain love
and how I can be "lover'd"?

485
00:41:14,656 --> 00:41:18,136
Once again, Mary's letter
had triggered an anxiety attack.

486
00:41:19,740 --> 00:41:21,780
Max knew nothing about love.

487
00:41:21,865 --> 00:41:25,665
It was as foreign to him as scuba diving

488
00:41:25,824 --> 00:41:29,737
and he'd had an appalling history
of getting it all wrong.

489
00:41:30,825 --> 00:41:32,425
One Valentine's Day

490
00:41:32,492 --> 00:41:37,486
he'd given Zelda Glutnik a gift
he was sure was appropriate.

491
00:41:43,576 --> 00:41:47,285
The only companion
that had ever warmed Max's bed

492
00:41:47,535 --> 00:41:49,491
was his hot water bottle.

493
00:41:51,244 --> 00:41:52,364
Romance and love

494
00:41:52,411 --> 00:41:55,483
was a mysterious language
he'd given up on.

495
00:41:56,411 --> 00:41:59,491
If only Mary had asked
how a toaster works

496
00:41:59,620 --> 00:42:03,020
or asked for an explanation
of the Chaos theory.

497
00:42:03,162 --> 00:42:07,440
If only there was
a mathematical equation for love.

498
00:42:09,246 --> 00:42:12,875
He kept eating and thinking.

499
00:42:28,082 --> 00:42:33,882
But love was not like Max's
Rubik's Cube. It could not be solved.

500
00:42:34,124 --> 00:42:37,514
No matter how he analysed it,
the results were negative.

501
00:42:38,124 --> 00:42:39,884
Beat it, creep!

502
00:42:39,958 --> 00:42:43,238
He felt love but couldn't articulate it.

503
00:42:43,375 --> 00:42:47,573
Its logic was as foreign to him as...
as a salad sandwich.

504
00:42:50,043 --> 00:42:52,159
The stars made more sense.

505
00:42:59,460 --> 00:43:02,580
12, have you responded
to the call? Over.

506
00:43:02,711 --> 00:43:05,951
The anxiety and stress were too much.

507
00:43:06,086 --> 00:43:11,922
The inscrutability of love finally won,
and Max's brain gave in.

508
00:43:21,421 --> 00:43:24,821
He was diagnosed
with severe depression and obesity

509
00:43:24,964 --> 00:43:30,322
and spent the next 8 months
institutionalised and bedridden.

510
00:43:30,631 --> 00:43:33,751
They marinated him
in a cocktail of drugs

511
00:43:33,881 --> 00:43:37,396
and performed
the usual "therapeutic" procedures.

512
00:43:42,966 --> 00:43:46,446
Meanwhile, Mary wondered and waited.

513
00:43:48,341 --> 00:43:51,299
Maybe Max's typewriter
had run out of ink.

514
00:43:51,758 --> 00:43:55,148
Maybe America had run out of ink.

515
00:43:55,884 --> 00:43:58,193
Maybe his pets had eaten him.

516
00:43:59,593 --> 00:44:01,823
Maybe it was her.

517
00:44:02,010 --> 00:44:06,401
Was she too demanding,
too boring, too...ugly?

518
00:44:14,720 --> 00:44:18,508
Filled with anger, confusion
and self-loathing,

519
00:44:18,762 --> 00:44:23,392
Mary tried to erase
the memory of her friend forever.

520
00:45:12,977 --> 00:45:14,171
Max had recovered.

521
00:45:14,310 --> 00:45:18,940
And life was balanced, safe
and symmetrical once again.

522
00:45:21,978 --> 00:45:26,298
But Mary still lingered in his mind.

523
00:45:26,478 --> 00:45:29,158
Half of him wanted to write to her
immediately.

524
00:45:29,270 --> 00:45:33,590
The other half didn't want to end up
a mental patient again.

525
00:45:33,771 --> 00:45:38,651
At least there was always Mr Ravioli
to be friends with.

526
00:45:38,855 --> 00:45:41,733
He was a much safer option.

527
00:45:42,897 --> 00:45:46,651
He wondered what Mary was doing
right now.

528
00:45:47,773 --> 00:45:50,453
But she was far from content

529
00:45:50,565 --> 00:45:56,401
and struggled on by herself,
saving her money for a rainy day.

530
00:46:04,150 --> 00:46:06,310
Life went on as usual for Max

531
00:46:06,400 --> 00:46:10,120
and even though he opted
for order and stability,

532
00:46:10,275 --> 00:46:13,585
misfortune was never far away.

533
00:46:43,029 --> 00:46:46,869
Luckily, his manslaughter charges
were dismissed

534
00:46:47,030 --> 00:46:49,870
because he was labelled
mentally deficient

535
00:46:49,988 --> 00:46:54,028
and unlikely to have a motive
for killing a mime artist...

536
00:46:54,197 --> 00:46:55,312
Oop.

537
00:46:55,447 --> 00:46:56,926
..unlike most people.

538
00:46:58,823 --> 00:47:02,303
From then on,
Max cooled himself differently

539
00:47:02,448 --> 00:47:04,848
and things went back to normal

540
00:47:04,949 --> 00:47:10,669
until after his 48th birthday,
when his numbers finally came up.

541
00:47:10,908 --> 00:47:13,228
Welcome
to the New York Lottery

542
00:47:13,325 --> 00:47:15,445
and these are tonight's
winning numbers

543
00:47:15,533 --> 00:47:18,693
3, 5,

544
00:47:18,825 --> 00:47:24,545
6, 9,

545
00:47:24,784 --> 00:47:30,495
11 and 12!

546
00:48:12,457 --> 00:48:14,337
Max was sensible
with his sudden wealth

547
00:48:14,415 --> 00:48:17,535
and had bought a lifetime supply
of chocolate

548
00:48:17,666 --> 00:48:20,626
and the complete Noblet collection.

549
00:48:24,958 --> 00:48:28,234
Two of his life goals had come true.

550
00:48:28,459 --> 00:48:31,299
But he still had a lot of money

551
00:48:31,417 --> 00:48:33,777
so decided to give it to lvy...

552
00:48:35,210 --> 00:48:38,282
..who was also very sensible...

553
00:49:12,131 --> 00:49:16,010
..until her own numbers came up.

554
00:49:24,757 --> 00:49:28,597
Ivy willed everything
to the local cat shelter,

555
00:49:28,758 --> 00:49:33,678
whose owner relocated
her kind donation to his bank account,

556
00:49:33,883 --> 00:49:40,123
his wife's new breasts, a Ferrari
and enough fuel to get to Mexico.

557
00:49:48,218 --> 00:49:52,058
Despite achieving all his life's goals,

558
00:49:52,219 --> 00:49:56,539
Max still felt incomplete.

559
00:49:56,719 --> 00:50:00,119
Mr Ravioli just wasn't
cutting the mustard anymore

560
00:50:00,262 --> 00:50:05,211
and seemed more interested
in his self-help books.

561
00:50:05,554 --> 00:50:08,794
Mary had given Max
a taste of real friendship

562
00:50:08,929 --> 00:50:12,285
and there was just no comparison.

563
00:50:13,096 --> 00:50:15,176
She missed him too

564
00:50:15,263 --> 00:50:18,061
but no longer saved to see him.

565
00:50:19,389 --> 00:50:23,143
She now saved
for a different reason.

566
00:50:33,224 --> 00:50:38,617
One day Mr Ravioli got up,
left and never came back.

567
00:50:42,850 --> 00:50:46,170
Max sought Dr Hazelhof's advice.

568
00:50:47,767 --> 00:50:52,647
He told Max that true friendship
is seen through the heart,

569
00:50:52,851 --> 00:50:54,771
not through the eyes,

570
00:50:54,852 --> 00:51:02,532
and that it was time he wrote to Mary
to reveal his true self, warts and all.

571
00:51:02,853 --> 00:51:05,731
Max understood.

572
00:51:23,272 --> 00:51:26,032
Dear Mary Daisy Dinkle,

573
00:51:26,147 --> 00:51:28,615
there is something I have to tell you

574
00:51:28,814 --> 00:51:32,523
which will explain
why I have not written.

575
00:51:32,773 --> 00:51:38,962
Each time I received one of your letters,
I had a severe anxiety attack.

576
00:51:39,315 --> 00:51:43,795
This is because recently,
while I was in a mental institution,

577
00:51:43,983 --> 00:51:50,623
they diagnosed that I have a new thing
called Asperger's syndrome,

578
00:51:50,900 --> 00:51:57,940
which is a neurobiological,
pervasive, developmental disability.

579
00:51:58,234 --> 00:52:01,834
I prefer "Aspie" for short.

580
00:52:01,985 --> 00:52:05,785
I will now list some of the traits
of an Aspie.

581
00:52:08,444 --> 00:52:13,204
No.1 - I find the world
very confusing and chaotic

582
00:52:13,403 --> 00:52:18,563
because my mind
is very literal and logical.

583
00:52:22,029 --> 00:52:28,184
2 - I have trouble understanding
the expressions on people's faces.

584
00:52:28,530 --> 00:52:36,528
When I was younger, I made a book
to help me when I was confused.

585
00:52:39,739 --> 00:52:43,049
I still have trouble with some people.

586
00:52:43,323 --> 00:52:46,483
Ivy was hard to understand
because of her wrinkles

587
00:52:46,615 --> 00:52:50,051
and because her eyebrows weren't real.

588
00:52:51,449 --> 00:52:53,769
3 - I have bad handwriting,

589
00:52:53,866 --> 00:52:56,786
am hypersensitive...

590
00:52:56,908 --> 00:52:59,548
..clumsy

591
00:52:59,658 --> 00:53:03,014
and can get very concerned.

592
00:53:06,701 --> 00:53:14,176
4 - I like solving problems.
Ivy said this is a good thing.

593
00:53:17,077 --> 00:53:22,197
And finally No.5 -
I have trouble expressing my emotions.

594
00:53:22,411 --> 00:53:27,411
Dr Bernard Hazelhof says
my brain is defective

595
00:53:27,620 --> 00:53:33,100
but one day there will be a cure
for my disability.

596
00:53:33,329 --> 00:53:35,729
I do not like it when he says this.

597
00:53:35,829 --> 00:53:40,709
I do not feel disabled, defective
or I need to be cured.

598
00:53:40,913 --> 00:53:43,791
I like being an Aspie.

599
00:53:43,997 --> 00:53:48,070
It would be like trying to change
the colour of my eyes.

600
00:53:50,081 --> 00:53:54,041
There is one thing
I wish I could change, however.

601
00:53:55,915 --> 00:53:58,435
I wish I could cry properly.

602
00:54:01,041 --> 00:54:06,201
I squeeze and squeeze
but nothing...comes out.

603
00:54:06,416 --> 00:54:09,776
I cry when I cut onions
but this does not count.

604
00:54:09,917 --> 00:54:12,717
Anyway, do you like the word
"cumquat"?

605
00:54:12,834 --> 00:54:14,874
It is a type of fruit.

606
00:54:14,959 --> 00:54:17,678
Do you have
a favourite-sounding word?

607
00:54:17,876 --> 00:54:21,636
My top 5 are ointment, bumblebee,

608
00:54:21,793 --> 00:54:25,033
Vladivostok, banana

609
00:54:25,169 --> 00:54:27,046
and testicle.

610
00:54:28,919 --> 00:54:32,832
I have also invented some new words

611
00:54:33,086 --> 00:54:40,197
"confuzzled", which is being confused
and puzzled at the same time,

612
00:54:40,587 --> 00:54:45,183
"snirt", which is a cross between
snow and dirt,

613
00:54:45,463 --> 00:54:47,783
and "smushables"...

614
00:54:47,880 --> 00:54:53,360
..which are squashed groceries
you find at the bottom of the bag.

615
00:54:53,589 --> 00:54:57,429
I have sent a letter
to the Oxford Dictionary people

616
00:54:57,589 --> 00:55:00,869
asking them to include my words

617
00:55:01,006 --> 00:55:04,203
but I have not heard back.

618
00:55:04,424 --> 00:55:08,664
It is now time for me to go
to my Overeaters Anonymous meeting.

619
00:55:08,841 --> 00:55:12,321
There is a woman there
called Marjorie Buttersworth

620
00:55:12,466 --> 00:55:14,775
who confuzzles me.

621
00:55:14,966 --> 00:55:18,846
She kisses me without my permission

622
00:55:19,009 --> 00:55:25,608
so tonight I have decided to rub onions
under my armpits to repel her.

623
00:55:26,010 --> 00:55:30,800
Your friend in America,
Max Jerry Horowitz.

624
00:55:35,552 --> 00:55:37,872
PS. Please find enclosed

625
00:55:37,969 --> 00:55:41,723
some chocolate-covered ants
I found at the deli.

626
00:55:43,137 --> 00:55:47,137
PPS. Not much has happened
since I last wrote

627
00:55:47,304 --> 00:55:53,652
except for my manslaughter charges,
lotto win and lvy's death.

628
00:55:57,305 --> 00:56:00,585
Mary was thrilled
Max had finally written

629
00:56:00,722 --> 00:56:03,442
and suddenly had a fabulous idea.

630
00:56:03,556 --> 00:56:05,433
A-ha!

631
00:56:39,268 --> 00:56:43,068
Mary and Max's friendship
was resuscitated

632
00:56:43,227 --> 00:56:48,267
and her tears were the best gift
he'd ever received.

633
00:56:48,478 --> 00:56:52,630
Inside Max's head
his brain was smiling.

634
00:56:54,395 --> 00:56:56,915
Loaded up with bizarre forms
of chocolate,

635
00:56:57,021 --> 00:57:01,381
their letters flew thick and fast
between the continents.

636
00:57:01,563 --> 00:57:04,843
Max learnt to read Mary's letters
with caution

637
00:57:04,980 --> 00:57:08,893
and at the slightest tingle of tension,
he would stop,

638
00:57:09,147 --> 00:57:12,776
take his medication
and soothe his nerves.

639
00:57:13,023 --> 00:57:18,783
Each letter he would iron, laminate
and file in a special place,

640
00:57:19,023 --> 00:57:22,060
which also soothed his nerves.

641
00:57:26,566 --> 00:57:30,957
He enjoyed answering her questions
and solving her puzzles like

642
00:57:31,233 --> 00:57:33,993
Do sheep shrink when it rains?

643
00:57:34,108 --> 00:57:38,028
Why do old men
wear their pants so high?

644
00:57:38,192 --> 00:57:43,352
Do gooses get goosebumps
and why is bellybutton lint blue?

645
00:57:43,568 --> 00:57:45,208
Are there Noblets in heaven?

646
00:57:45,276 --> 00:57:49,876
And if a taxi goes backwards,
does the driver owe you money?

647
00:57:50,069 --> 00:57:55,829
In turn, Mary simply enjoyed
hearing about Max's fascinating life

648
00:57:56,069 --> 00:57:58,424
how many people
he'd counted littering...

649
00:58:04,029 --> 00:58:06,269
..how the latest Henry had died...

650
00:58:15,905 --> 00:58:19,056
..and new recipes he'd invented
for chicken.

651
00:58:22,781 --> 00:58:24,781
Each nourished the other

652
00:58:24,865 --> 00:58:27,665
and, as Mary grew taller,

653
00:58:27,782 --> 00:58:29,742
Max grew wider

654
00:58:29,824 --> 00:58:35,376
their friendship becoming stronger
than the glue on Mary's Noblets.

655
00:58:39,908 --> 00:58:42,748
Although Max found solace in Mary,

656
00:58:42,867 --> 00:58:46,107
he still found the rest of the world
bewildering.

657
00:58:46,242 --> 00:58:48,002
And he couldn't understand

658
00:58:48,076 --> 00:58:51,036
why he was seen as the odd one

659
00:58:51,159 --> 00:58:54,037
while everyone else
was considered normal.

660
00:58:56,035 --> 00:58:59,515
Humans were endlessly illogical.

661
00:58:59,660 --> 00:59:04,820
Why did they throw out food when
there were children starving in lndia?

662
00:59:05,036 --> 00:59:09,676
Why did they clear the rainforests
when they needed the oxygen?

663
00:59:09,870 --> 00:59:16,470
And why did they create bus timetables
when they never ran on time?

664
00:59:16,746 --> 00:59:23,266
He agreed with his favourite physicist
that there are only two things infinite

665
00:59:23,538 --> 00:59:27,418
the universe and man's stupidity.

666
00:59:29,206 --> 00:59:34,846
And for Mary, even though
Max filled her with confidence...

667
00:59:35,081 --> 00:59:36,041
Bullseye!

668
00:59:36,082 --> 00:59:39,562
..her world was far from perfect.

669
00:59:39,707 --> 00:59:43,097
The grip of love had her by the throat.

670
01:00:03,877 --> 01:00:09,237
At 4.59pm, on the 8th of the 8th 1988...

671
01:00:11,461 --> 01:00:16,021
..Noel Norman Dinkle
attached his last string

672
01:00:16,211 --> 01:00:22,331
and, after 40 years
and 40 million tea bags, he retired.

673
01:00:22,587 --> 01:00:27,507
To celebrate, Noel announced
he was retiring from taxidermy

674
01:00:27,713 --> 01:00:31,433
and taking up metal detecting instead.

675
01:00:31,588 --> 01:00:35,137
But, sadly, it was not a hobby
he had for long.

676
01:01:12,635 --> 01:01:15,995
In his will, Noel had left Mary
some money

677
01:01:16,135 --> 01:01:20,970
so she decided to go to university
and study disorders of the mind,

678
01:01:21,261 --> 01:01:25,061
yearning to learn more about her friend.

679
01:01:25,220 --> 01:01:31,100
Mary was as popular at university
as she was at school.

680
01:01:31,346 --> 01:01:34,706
Damian went there too,
aching to be a Thespian.

681
01:01:34,846 --> 01:01:37,726
Hi there, M-M-Mary.

682
01:01:37,846 --> 01:01:41,395
Hi...hello!

683
01:01:50,890 --> 01:01:53,610
That was damn f-f-funny!

684
01:02:24,644 --> 01:02:30,284
Hey, Damian,
your mum's roses look fab!

685
01:02:30,519 --> 01:02:32,999
Oh, th-th-th-thanks, Mary.

686
01:02:33,103 --> 01:02:35,543
Um, M-Mary,
can I tell you something?

687
01:02:35,645 --> 01:02:37,485
Sure, babe!

688
01:02:37,562 --> 01:02:42,556
Um, um, you've got d-d-d-d-dog's poo
on your shoe.

689
01:02:54,939 --> 01:02:56,859
Dear Max,

690
01:02:56,939 --> 01:02:58,859
I have been such an idiot.

691
01:02:58,940 --> 01:03:01,380
I've wasted all my money
on something pointless

692
01:03:01,482 --> 01:03:03,359
when I should have been saving
to see you.

693
01:03:05,399 --> 01:03:08,479
I know love upsets you
so I won't go on about it.

694
01:03:08,607 --> 01:03:12,927
All I want to say is that love
is obviously not for me.

695
01:03:13,108 --> 01:03:17,388
I hope you are well and enjoy
the chocolate cigarettes I've enclosed.

696
01:03:17,567 --> 01:03:18,886
Love Mary.

697
01:03:33,652 --> 01:03:36,292
Oh, you should be ashamed!

698
01:03:36,402 --> 01:03:38,632
- Come on, baby. Let's go.
- Oh, Mum...

699
01:03:38,819 --> 01:03:41,891
I told you never to talk to strangers.

700
01:03:50,946 --> 01:03:56,066
Noel's sudden death
had filled Vera with remorse and guilt

701
01:03:56,280 --> 01:04:00,671
and she coped
in the only way she knew.

702
01:05:36,750 --> 01:05:38,310
Dear Max,

703
01:05:38,376 --> 01:05:41,856
our wedding day was everything
I have ever dreamt,

704
01:05:42,001 --> 01:05:44,921
making up for the terrible year I've had.

705
01:05:47,293 --> 01:05:50,013
Although all the guests
were Damian's family and friends,

706
01:05:50,127 --> 01:05:52,118
I felt very welcome.

707
01:05:55,878 --> 01:06:00,478
Damian is so perfect.
He even made my wedding dress.

708
01:06:00,670 --> 01:06:01,950
And for our honeymoon

709
01:06:02,003 --> 01:06:05,359
he took me to Mykonos
his favourite island in Greece.

710
01:06:05,629 --> 01:06:07,269
I got to ride a donkey

711
01:06:07,337 --> 01:06:10,857
and found the perfect gift for Len.

712
01:06:11,005 --> 01:06:14,965
Poor Len, he's still struggling
with his agoraphobia.

713
01:06:16,380 --> 01:06:18,900
Aaaaahhhh!

714
01:06:23,214 --> 01:06:25,894
Damian and I are so similar.

715
01:06:26,006 --> 01:06:30,045
He even has his own penfriend, who lives
on a sheep farm in New Zealand.

716
01:06:34,007 --> 01:06:35,967
Mary...M-M-M-Mary.

717
01:06:36,049 --> 01:06:38,847
Mary...M-M-M-Mary.

718
01:06:39,050 --> 01:06:40,642
Ohhh.

719
01:06:41,800 --> 01:06:46,032
Mary was bursting with self-esteem

720
01:06:46,301 --> 01:06:49,181
and her confidence
was almost unbearable.

721
01:06:51,259 --> 01:06:53,899
At university, she shone

722
01:06:54,010 --> 01:06:59,164
and took it upon herself
to cure the world of mental illness.

723
01:07:05,845 --> 01:07:09,205
She did her thesis
on Asperger's syndrome

724
01:07:09,345 --> 01:07:13,224
and used Max as her case study.

725
01:07:13,512 --> 01:07:16,072
Her professors
were thoroughly impressed

726
01:07:16,179 --> 01:07:19,899
and her writing praised far and wide.

727
01:07:20,055 --> 01:07:23,575
Soon, publishers queued
to print her unique insight

728
01:07:23,722 --> 01:07:31,042
